1
00:00:22,381 --> 00:00:25,036
<i>Look at the water.</i>

2
00:00:26,927 --> 00:00:28,787
<i>- What's this?
- Towel.</i>

3
00:00:28,846 --> 00:00:31,085
<i>- What kind of towel?
- Super towel.</i>

4
00:00:31,140 --> 00:00:34,673
<i>What does the super towel get
the super boy? Super clean, right?</i>

5
00:00:34,727 --> 00:00:36,718
<i>Super boy.</i>

6
00:00:36,895 --> 00:00:40,678
<i>That's super boy.
Super, super clean.</i>

7
00:00:41,191 --> 00:00:42,969
<i>Super wet.</i>

8
00:00:45,654 --> 00:00:47,113
<i>Who's this?</i>

9
00:00:47,114 --> 00:00:48,594
<i>Jeremiah.</i>

10
00:00:49,533 --> 00:00:52,354
<i>He's a Jeremiah.</i>

11
00:00:52,411 --> 00:00:54,319
It's Jeremiah versus Moby Dick.

12
00:00:54,371 --> 00:00:57,656
<i>Jeremiah was a bullfrog</i>

13
00:00:58,292 --> 00:01:00,899
<i>Was a good friend of mine</i>

14
00:01:01,003 --> 00:01:05,580
<i>Never understood a
single word he said</i>

15
00:01:05,716 --> 00:01:09,534
<i>But I helped him drink his wine</i>

16
00:01:10,262 --> 00:01:13,416
<i>Singing joy to the world</i>

17
00:01:15,142 --> 00:01:17,880
<i>All the boys and girls now</i>

18
00:01:18,687 --> 00:01:21,129
<i>Joy to the fishes
In the deep blue sea</i>

19
00:01:21,190 --> 00:01:23,181
<i>Joy to you and me</i>

20
00:01:23,233 --> 00:01:26,138
- Yes, this is Dr. Cooper.
- What's that?

21
00:01:26,361 --> 00:01:29,099
Superman. Super nothing.

22
00:01:29,156 --> 00:01:31,894
That's super nothing!

23
00:01:32,368 --> 00:01:35,189
That's right, super boy is not
getting out of this tub...

24
00:01:35,245 --> 00:01:37,189
until he's as clean as a whistle.

25
00:01:37,623 --> 00:01:40,492
And super mom is going
to be very happy.

26
00:01:41,043 --> 00:01:43,200
I can't move that far.

27
00:01:43,253 --> 00:01:45,327
Come here. Come here. Head on down.

28
00:05:55,631 --> 00:05:57,455
Down onto the end.

29
00:05:58,384 --> 00:05:59,746
Come on.

30
00:06:02,137 --> 00:06:04,045
Right on down there.
There's a spot.

31
00:06:06,433 --> 00:06:08,175
- Harold.
- Sam.

32
00:06:14,024 --> 00:06:15,469
Christ.

33
00:06:18,153 --> 00:06:19,931
- Here, I'll get it.
- No, I'll get it.

34
00:06:19,988 --> 00:06:21,932
Let me put it in here.

35
00:06:22,783 --> 00:06:24,810
You can drive this to the cemetery.

36
00:06:24,868 --> 00:06:26,527
Oh, Christ.

37
00:06:28,539 --> 00:06:30,197
Were you here?

38
00:06:30,708 --> 00:06:34,407
What? No, Alex was staying
down here at the summer house.

39
00:06:34,461 --> 00:06:38,113
Sarah and I were up at the
Richmond place with the kids.

40
00:06:40,467 --> 00:06:42,993
- Well, you're looking fit.
- So are you.

41
00:06:59,653 --> 00:07:01,264
Listen...

42
00:07:02,364 --> 00:07:04,604
I want you to sit with Chloe.

43
00:07:04,700 --> 00:07:08,269
I've got to be up there, and it's a
little tricky with Alex's folks.

44
00:07:08,328 --> 00:07:09,809
I understand.

45
00:07:10,664 --> 00:07:12,323
Who's Chloe?

46
00:07:12,833 --> 00:07:14,907
It's Alex's girlfriend.

47
00:07:22,718 --> 00:07:24,626
I'll take care of her.

48
00:07:30,934 --> 00:07:32,961
Chloe, this is Michael.

49
00:07:32,978 --> 00:07:34,459
This is Chloe.

50
00:07:50,245 --> 00:07:51,726
Do you want to sit up with us?

51
00:07:51,789 --> 00:07:55,073
I'm going to sit here by
myself for a while, okay?

52
00:08:27,658 --> 00:08:29,233
Sometimes...

53
00:08:29,576 --> 00:08:32,528
it is hard for us to believe...

54
00:08:32,871 --> 00:08:34,779
that the good Lord had a plan.

55
00:08:35,541 --> 00:08:38,314
This is one of those times.

56
00:08:39,336 --> 00:08:42,822
I didn't know Alex
Marshall personally.

57
00:08:43,006 --> 00:08:46,207
But after speaking
with his loved ones...

58
00:08:46,260 --> 00:08:48,452
I feel that I do.

59
00:08:49,596 --> 00:08:54,672
A brilliant physics student at
the University of Michigan...

60
00:08:55,227 --> 00:09:00,219
who paradoxically chose to
turn his back on science...

61
00:09:00,774 --> 00:09:03,382
and taste of life
through a seemingly...

62
00:09:03,444 --> 00:09:06,728
random series of occupations.

63
00:09:29,011 --> 00:09:31,784
When a man like Alex...

64
00:09:31,847 --> 00:09:35,796
chooses to leave us, there is
something wrong in this world.

65
00:09:35,851 --> 00:09:37,960
I'm a pallbearer.

66
00:09:40,147 --> 00:09:42,755
This is not Alex.

67
00:09:43,358 --> 00:09:47,141
This is the empty
shell of his body.

68
00:09:48,363 --> 00:09:50,770
Alex is spirit now.

69
00:09:53,077 --> 00:09:56,728
But why are we left with this?

70
00:09:57,331 --> 00:09:59,358
It makes me angry.

71
00:09:59,416 --> 00:10:03,661
And I don't know what
to do with my anger.

72
00:10:04,630 --> 00:10:08,662
Are not the satisfactions
of being a good man...

73
00:10:08,717 --> 00:10:10,791
among our common men...

74
00:10:11,678 --> 00:10:15,129
great enough to sustain us anymore?

75
00:10:16,475 --> 00:10:20,459
Where did Alex's hope go?

76
00:10:22,064 --> 00:10:25,016
Maybe that is the
small resolution...

77
00:10:25,067 --> 00:10:27,936
we can take from here today.

78
00:10:29,405 --> 00:10:31,147
To try to...

79
00:10:31,448 --> 00:10:33,855
regain that hope...

80
00:10:35,035 --> 00:10:38,022
that must have eluded Alex.

81
00:11:13,657 --> 00:11:15,766
I did know Alex.

82
00:11:20,998 --> 00:11:23,072
And I loved him.

83
00:11:29,131 --> 00:11:32,996
See here today all those
people that Alex loved.

84
00:11:37,264 --> 00:11:41,129
Not all of us have been able to see
each other much these last years.

85
00:11:44,646 --> 00:11:46,886
But neither time nor distance...

86
00:11:48,317 --> 00:11:50,556
could break the bonds that we feel.

87
00:11:54,656 --> 00:11:57,893
Alex drew us together
from the beginning.

88
00:11:58,827 --> 00:12:01,399
Now he brings us together again.

89
00:12:04,500 --> 00:12:06,443
I don't know...

90
00:12:06,877 --> 00:12:08,868
why this happened.

91
00:12:11,590 --> 00:12:13,450
But I do know...

92
00:12:13,967 --> 00:12:17,204
that there was always
something about Alex...

93
00:12:19,390 --> 00:12:22,211
that was too good for this world.

94
00:12:31,693 --> 00:12:33,222
I only hope...

95
00:12:35,572 --> 00:12:37,931
that wherever he is now...

96
00:12:52,631 --> 00:12:53,495
Burial...

97
00:12:53,757 --> 00:12:57,326
will be at Westglade Memorial Park.

98
00:12:57,886 --> 00:12:59,664
There will be a reception...

99
00:12:59,722 --> 00:13:03,540
at the home of Harold
and Sarah Cooper...

100
00:13:03,600 --> 00:13:05,840
immediately following.

101
00:13:06,729 --> 00:13:08,589
And now...

102
00:13:09,398 --> 00:13:14,059
Karen Bowles, an old
college friend of Alex's...

103
00:13:14,236 --> 00:13:18,350
will play one of
Alex's favourite songs.

104
00:14:54,753 --> 00:14:57,076
Nicholas, this is Richard.

105
00:14:57,131 --> 00:14:59,039
Pleasure to meet you.

106
00:14:59,425 --> 00:15:02,080
I just met Meg earlier.
Just before the...

107
00:15:02,136 --> 00:15:03,830
Can I go over there?

108
00:15:05,681 --> 00:15:07,423
Sam Weber, this is Richard.

109
00:15:07,474 --> 00:15:12,170
Really enjoy your TV show.
My boys and I watch it all the time.

110
00:15:12,479 --> 00:15:16,547
Thank you. Well, we'll
see you out there.

111
00:15:39,673 --> 00:15:41,248
What is this?

112
00:16:23,926 --> 00:16:26,083
It's pretty strong stuff.

113
00:16:29,139 --> 00:16:30,881
I feel terrible.

114
00:16:33,352 --> 00:16:36,921
Last time I spoke with
Alex, we had a fight.

115
00:16:37,773 --> 00:16:39,551
I yelled at him.

116
00:16:40,484 --> 00:16:43,389
That's probably why
he killed himself.

117
00:16:51,954 --> 00:16:54,146
What was the argument about?

118
00:16:56,959 --> 00:16:59,780
I told him he was wasting his life.

119
00:17:17,730 --> 00:17:19,258
You all right?

120
00:17:19,773 --> 00:17:20,803
Yeah.

121
00:17:20,816 --> 00:17:24,800
I'm a little disappointed, though.
I wanted to ride up there.

122
00:17:27,406 --> 00:17:30,441
I've always wanted
to ride in a limo.

123
00:17:35,414 --> 00:17:37,357
I do half my work in limos.

124
00:17:37,416 --> 00:17:39,276
Are you a chauffeur?

125
00:17:40,044 --> 00:17:41,275
No, a journalist.

126
00:17:45,215 --> 00:17:47,741
<i>I write for People magazine.</i>

127
00:17:48,677 --> 00:17:51,249
I can't believe you're still
mad about that thing.

128
00:17:51,263 --> 00:17:53,171
This isn't the time. Just drop it.

129
00:17:53,265 --> 00:17:58,210
I will if you will. Today most of all
we should remember we're friends.

130
00:17:58,270 --> 00:18:00,261
And you're an actor?

131
00:18:14,328 --> 00:18:16,770
Nothing like you described.
Not at all.

132
00:18:16,830 --> 00:18:20,399
Not one of those people looks
like I thought they would.

133
00:18:20,459 --> 00:18:25,487
I can't believe these are the people
you've talked about all these years.

134
00:18:27,132 --> 00:18:30,499
I'd love to hear the way
you describe me to them.

135
00:19:51,467 --> 00:19:56,412
Amazing tradition. They throw you a
party on the one day you can't come.

136
00:20:02,269 --> 00:20:04,545
So how long were they together?

137
00:20:04,605 --> 00:20:06,299
Four months.

138
00:20:11,320 --> 00:20:13,180
Can't believe it.

139
00:20:13,697 --> 00:20:16,305
His funeral and she's stoned.

140
00:20:20,120 --> 00:20:23,523
Karen and I are staying here tonight.
We fly back to Detroit in the morning.

141
00:20:23,582 --> 00:20:24,778
Are you staying?

142
00:20:24,833 --> 00:20:27,240
I have to fly out
to Dallas tonight.

143
00:20:27,294 --> 00:20:30,614
I'm interviewing a 14-year-old
blind baton twirler.

144
00:20:33,133 --> 00:20:35,492
Where do you get those stories?

145
00:20:36,845 --> 00:20:39,417
It's just good
investigative journalism.

146
00:20:39,681 --> 00:20:41,210
- How's your life?
- Great.

147
00:20:41,266 --> 00:20:43,044
- Yours?
- Not so great.

148
00:20:44,478 --> 00:20:46,256
We're telling the truth.

149
00:20:46,355 --> 00:20:48,346
You heard about my divorce.

150
00:20:48,440 --> 00:20:50,300
Yeah, I'm really sorry.

151
00:20:51,026 --> 00:20:52,685
Are you J.T. Lancer?

152
00:20:52,820 --> 00:20:55,511
No, no, that's the
character I play.

153
00:20:55,572 --> 00:20:56,852
I'm Sam Weber.

154
00:20:57,157 --> 00:21:00,311
Can I have your autograph,
whoever you are?

155
00:21:00,828 --> 00:21:03,186
You think it's time we should
be thinking about Alex?

156
00:21:03,247 --> 00:21:04,478
I'll give you a buck.

157
00:21:04,707 --> 00:21:06,566
Okay, you're on.

158
00:21:13,132 --> 00:21:15,953
You'd never get a crowd
this big at my funeral.

159
00:21:16,176 --> 00:21:19,911
Come on. I'll come,
and I'll bring a date.

160
00:21:22,599 --> 00:21:25,753
I know this is hard for you,
but it's all beautiful.

161
00:21:26,603 --> 00:21:28,511
We put on a great funeral here.

162
00:21:28,564 --> 00:21:30,258
Maybe I'll have mine here too.

163
00:21:30,315 --> 00:21:34,015
We give first preference to people
who kill themselves in our bathroom.

164
00:21:37,489 --> 00:21:40,145
That was a terrible thing to say.

165
00:21:40,909 --> 00:21:43,067
I don't know why I said that.

166
00:21:45,372 --> 00:21:48,063
That's why I don't smoke anymore.
Dope makes me stupid.

167
00:21:48,208 --> 00:21:49,819
You talking about me?

168
00:21:49,918 --> 00:21:52,444
Here's the guy who did this to me.

169
00:21:52,629 --> 00:21:54,988
I no longer know how to
handle myself stoned.

170
00:21:55,049 --> 00:21:57,870
You don't have to handle
yourself with us.

171
00:21:59,094 --> 00:22:01,002
Will you marry me?

172
00:22:03,223 --> 00:22:04,799
Both of you?

173
00:22:09,646 --> 00:22:12,682
That shit they got about your
marriage wasn't from me.

174
00:22:12,733 --> 00:22:15,568
I didn't know they were doing a
story, or why you don't believe me.

175
00:22:15,569 --> 00:22:17,429
- Let's drop it!
- Say you believe me.

176
00:22:17,488 --> 00:22:19,764
I believe you.
I always believe you.

177
00:22:19,865 --> 00:22:23,730
Honest to God, I know it's crap.
That's why I'm getting out.

178
00:22:23,827 --> 00:22:26,435
Yeah? What're you going to do?

179
00:22:26,872 --> 00:22:28,815
I'm opening a club.

180
00:22:28,916 --> 00:22:30,444
No shit!

181
00:22:30,709 --> 00:22:34,159
Like Elaine's, but hipper.
Elaine's is dead.

182
00:22:36,882 --> 00:22:38,327
You got the money?

183
00:22:38,592 --> 00:22:39,990
Almost, almost.

184
00:22:40,844 --> 00:22:42,289
Well, let me know.

185
00:22:42,346 --> 00:22:43,744
What do you mean?

186
00:22:44,890 --> 00:22:46,881
I might be interested.

187
00:22:47,893 --> 00:22:49,172
Really?

188
00:22:51,563 --> 00:22:53,970
So you and Alex were staying here?

189
00:22:53,982 --> 00:22:56,258
We have a room downstairs.

190
00:22:56,276 --> 00:22:57,674
Well, we did.

191
00:22:57,736 --> 00:22:59,181
I do.

192
00:23:00,364 --> 00:23:02,106
I found him.

193
00:23:02,116 --> 00:23:03,774
God, it must have been awful.

194
00:23:03,867 --> 00:23:06,274
It was. It was a real mess.

195
00:23:06,870 --> 00:23:08,565
What will you do now?

196
00:23:09,081 --> 00:23:10,526
We cleaned it up.

197
00:23:14,336 --> 00:23:16,078
Are you going to stay here?

198
00:23:16,171 --> 00:23:18,245
Yeah, till Sarah kicks me out.

199
00:23:18,298 --> 00:23:20,871
I'm sure she'd never do that.

200
00:23:24,263 --> 00:23:27,001
That's right, if I may.
That's why I'm calling, Jim.

201
00:23:27,057 --> 00:23:31,089
That way, I can have a piece for
you this week and next week...

202
00:23:31,186 --> 00:23:34,091
Give me a break.
I'll fly to Dallas on Monday.

203
00:23:34,148 --> 00:23:36,921
She won't regain her
eyesight over the weekend.

204
00:23:37,025 --> 00:23:40,262
I know, but I think I've got
something good right here.

205
00:23:40,362 --> 00:23:42,555
I don't know. It's
about everything.

206
00:23:42,656 --> 00:23:45,430
Suicide, despair, where
did our hope go...

207
00:23:45,492 --> 00:23:47,981
Lost hope. That's it, lost hope.

208
00:23:48,996 --> 00:23:50,904
You think everything's boring.

209
00:23:50,998 --> 00:23:54,448
You wouldn't say that if it
was the "Lost Hope Diet."

210
00:23:59,006 --> 00:24:00,700
Michael's office called.

211
00:24:00,758 --> 00:24:02,997
He doesn't have to be
in Dallas till Monday.

212
00:24:03,093 --> 00:24:04,669
He asked to stay the weekend.

213
00:24:04,762 --> 00:24:07,120
Harold, you didn't.

214
00:24:07,181 --> 00:24:10,298
What could I say? He knows
that Sam is staying...

215
00:24:10,350 --> 00:24:12,377
and Karen, Richard and Meg.

216
00:24:12,478 --> 00:24:14,469
Meg's not staying.

217
00:24:15,105 --> 00:24:17,345
Well, actually...

218
00:24:20,194 --> 00:24:21,639
Where will we put them?

219
00:24:21,695 --> 00:24:23,112
We'll make room.

220
00:24:23,113 --> 00:24:24,689
Hi, guys.

221
00:24:28,077 --> 00:24:29,652
- Hey, Nick.
- How you doing?

222
00:24:31,080 --> 00:24:32,394
Good.

223
00:24:33,207 --> 00:24:35,115
Advertising's all right.

224
00:24:35,125 --> 00:24:38,243
A lot of bullshit with
clients and stuff.

225
00:24:38,545 --> 00:24:40,121
But it's all right.

226
00:24:40,255 --> 00:24:42,199
It's a decent living.

227
00:24:42,508 --> 00:24:45,543
Not as much as we spend, of course.

228
00:24:45,552 --> 00:24:48,837
Just kidding. It's exactly
as much as we spend.

229
00:24:48,889 --> 00:24:53,466
What have you got, an oil leak?
Can I give you a hand?

230
00:24:59,441 --> 00:25:01,183
I think I got it.

231
00:25:05,155 --> 00:25:08,190
I feel like I have never
been alone in my own house.

232
00:25:08,575 --> 00:25:13,272
Never. Either Richard is there,
or the boys or the housekeeper.

233
00:25:13,372 --> 00:25:16,489
Remember those lab rats who went
crazy when deprived of privacy?

234
00:25:16,583 --> 00:25:18,693
They're living with you too?

235
00:25:19,753 --> 00:25:22,195
- Should we push the beds together?
- Why?

236
00:25:22,256 --> 00:25:24,744
Okay. How about further apart?

237
00:25:25,676 --> 00:25:28,793
In January we open in Greensboro.

238
00:25:28,846 --> 00:25:32,130
And in April, our second
store in Charleston.

239
00:25:32,224 --> 00:25:34,002
How many is that now?

240
00:25:34,101 --> 00:25:36,424
Twenty-seven and twenty-eight.

241
00:25:37,020 --> 00:25:40,221
Better watch out. Some big
monster will buy you.

242
00:25:40,274 --> 00:25:42,051
We've had offers.

243
00:25:44,570 --> 00:25:47,474
Who would've thought we'd
both make so much bread?

244
00:25:47,573 --> 00:25:49,600
Two revolutionaries.

245
00:25:51,827 --> 00:25:54,352
Good thing it's not
important to us.

246
00:25:57,207 --> 00:25:59,981
Fuck them if they
can't take a joke.

247
00:26:05,132 --> 00:26:07,490
Chloe. Hi, you there?

248
00:26:12,514 --> 00:26:14,422
I just wanted to...

249
00:26:15,309 --> 00:26:16,671
make sure you're okay.

250
00:26:16,769 --> 00:26:19,008
- Yeah, I'm fine.
- Good.

251
00:26:21,690 --> 00:26:23,550
Thanks, Michael.

252
00:27:34,471 --> 00:27:35,869
Come along?

253
00:27:35,931 --> 00:27:37,590
Are you kidding?

254
00:28:21,351 --> 00:28:24,173
So I'm in the Philadelphia
Public Defender's office.

255
00:28:24,229 --> 00:28:28,048
<i>My clients were the scum of
the earth. Extreme repulsivos.</i>

256
00:28:29,109 --> 00:28:31,717
One of them got
caught in the house.

257
00:28:31,779 --> 00:28:35,430
He and his friends beat up the
husband, rape the wife...

258
00:28:35,491 --> 00:28:37,517
then tried to blow the place up.
When I ask what happened, he says:

259
00:28:37,576 --> 00:28:39,056
"I was in Montreal at the time."

260
00:28:39,119 --> 00:28:42,653
Who'd you think your clients would be?
Grumpy and Sneezy?

261
00:28:42,915 --> 00:28:44,739
Huey and Bobby.

262
00:28:45,167 --> 00:28:47,443
I don't know. I just
didn't think they'd be...

263
00:28:47,544 --> 00:28:48,824
so guilty.

264
00:28:50,964 --> 00:28:52,279
And then?

265
00:28:52,674 --> 00:28:53,954
Then I left.

266
00:28:54,009 --> 00:28:58,159
A law school friend is at a firm
in Atlanta doing real estate law.

267
00:28:58,263 --> 00:28:59,708
I went to see them.

268
00:29:00,140 --> 00:29:02,249
The offices were very clean...

269
00:29:02,309 --> 00:29:04,549
and the clients were
only raping the land...

270
00:29:04,645 --> 00:29:07,680
and then of course
there was the money.

271
00:29:08,399 --> 00:29:10,591
<i>El greedo strikes again.</i>

272
00:29:10,609 --> 00:29:12,090
Sarah has that robe.

273
00:29:12,361 --> 00:29:14,221
Not this weekend she doesn't.

274
00:29:14,279 --> 00:29:16,472
I always jump her
when she wears it.

275
00:29:16,532 --> 00:29:18,890
Harold, don't you
have any other music?

276
00:29:18,951 --> 00:29:20,147
Like, from this century?

277
00:29:20,202 --> 00:29:22,193
There is no other
music in my house.

278
00:29:22,246 --> 00:29:25,731
There's been a lot of terrific
music in the last 10 years.

279
00:29:25,791 --> 00:29:26,940
Like what?

280
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:31,447
How about you, Michael?
Tell us about bigtime journalism.

281
00:29:32,464 --> 00:29:35,155
Where I work we have
only one editorial rule:

282
00:29:35,217 --> 00:29:39,284
No writing longer than an average
person can read during an average crap.

283
00:29:40,931 --> 00:29:43,088
I'm tired of having my
work read in the can.

284
00:29:43,142 --> 00:29:45,215
People read Dostoyevsky in the can.

285
00:29:45,269 --> 00:29:47,046
But they can't finish it.

286
00:29:48,897 --> 00:29:51,671
This certainly is a familiar scene.

287
00:29:53,277 --> 00:29:56,050
I'm feeling very guilty about it.

288
00:29:56,321 --> 00:29:59,309
I'm happy to be here, but
I'm sick about the reason.

289
00:30:00,117 --> 00:30:01,692
I'm going to bed.

290
00:30:02,494 --> 00:30:04,454
I'm sorry. We could talk
about something else.

291
00:30:04,455 --> 00:30:07,525
That's okay. I'm exhausted.
Good night, everyone.

292
00:30:07,624 --> 00:30:09,153
I'll be up in a minute.

293
00:30:09,209 --> 00:30:10,868
Good night, Sarah.

294
00:30:12,337 --> 00:30:13,652
Harold, I'm sorry.

295
00:30:15,132 --> 00:30:16,495
We all feel that way.

296
00:30:17,593 --> 00:30:19,750
I forget what this is like.

297
00:30:20,345 --> 00:30:22,622
In L.A., I don't know who to trust.

298
00:30:22,723 --> 00:30:25,248
I feel like everybody
wants something from me.

299
00:30:25,350 --> 00:30:27,377
I know that sounds
terrible, but it's true.

300
00:30:27,436 --> 00:30:30,423
Tell me about it.
It's a cold world out there.

301
00:30:30,481 --> 00:30:33,432
Sometimes I think I'm
getting frosty myself.

302
00:30:33,776 --> 00:30:36,099
I don't know what
people think about me.

303
00:30:36,195 --> 00:30:39,846
I don't know why they like me,
or even if they do like me.

304
00:30:40,449 --> 00:30:42,558
You don't have that problem here.

305
00:30:45,496 --> 00:30:46,976
You know I don't like you.

306
00:30:48,957 --> 00:30:50,153
Me either.

307
00:30:50,501 --> 00:30:51,815
Ditto.

308
00:30:51,877 --> 00:30:53,619
So relax.

309
00:30:55,506 --> 00:30:57,330
Assholes.

310
00:31:24,159 --> 00:31:25,818
I was just coming down.

311
00:31:25,869 --> 00:31:27,184
Don't.

312
00:31:33,419 --> 00:31:35,327
What are we doing?

313
00:31:40,217 --> 00:31:44,367
I didn't get to talk to you before.
You got me stoned too quick.

314
00:31:44,471 --> 00:31:46,165
But I'm okay now.

315
00:31:46,265 --> 00:31:48,541
I'm just drunk and therefore brave.

316
00:31:48,600 --> 00:31:51,801
I've always been a
cowardly drunk myself.

317
00:31:52,938 --> 00:31:55,178
I bought the land three years ago.

318
00:31:55,232 --> 00:32:00,141
He and Chloe were working on it. There's
an old house they were fixing up.

319
00:32:00,529 --> 00:32:04,312
It's really pretty. I can take you
out there tomorrow if you want.

320
00:32:06,618 --> 00:32:09,274
That's what I don't get. It's
one of the things I don't get.

321
00:32:09,329 --> 00:32:11,771
He was really involved in that.

322
00:32:11,832 --> 00:32:14,108
It seemed to really
mean something to him.

323
00:32:14,168 --> 00:32:18,496
I went with him three weeks
ago to buy a table saw.

324
00:32:19,423 --> 00:32:21,580
Why does he do a thing like that?

325
00:32:22,760 --> 00:32:24,537
I should've known.

326
00:32:26,930 --> 00:32:29,503
- How could you know?
- Nobody knew.

327
00:32:29,725 --> 00:32:31,046
I can't even believe it now.

328
00:32:31,101 --> 00:32:33,508
I don't care. I should've known.

329
00:32:34,772 --> 00:32:37,297
All I want is a little warmth.

330
00:32:43,739 --> 00:32:44,970
What?

331
00:32:49,953 --> 00:32:51,648
Sweetheart?

332
00:33:00,547 --> 00:33:02,705
Did I ever tell you...

333
00:33:03,217 --> 00:33:05,623
what happened to me in Vietnam?

334
00:33:17,898 --> 00:33:20,719
It's a fucking bat, and I
think it touched my hair!

335
00:33:20,818 --> 00:33:23,094
I hate them! They're
like rats with wings.

336
00:33:23,153 --> 00:33:24,729
No, pigeons are rats with wings.

337
00:33:24,780 --> 00:33:28,313
- They're harmless. They eat mosquitoes.
- I'm going to wash my hair and puke.

338
00:33:28,367 --> 00:33:30,939
- Puke first, of course.
- Stand aside!

339
00:33:33,997 --> 00:33:36,273
That's cashmere! Give me that.

340
00:33:40,796 --> 00:33:42,490
I'll be right bat.

341
00:33:47,344 --> 00:33:48,789
Where'd it go?

342
00:33:51,598 --> 00:33:52,961
Listen for it.

343
00:33:53,517 --> 00:33:55,875
It makes weird sound. Kind of:

344
00:34:00,649 --> 00:34:02,391
It's quiet in here.

345
00:34:04,236 --> 00:34:05,895
It's too quiet.

346
00:34:10,576 --> 00:34:11,807
Shit!

347
00:34:12,161 --> 00:34:13,392
Look out, Nick!

348
00:34:14,830 --> 00:34:17,188
Behind you. Here, let me open this.

349
00:34:17,249 --> 00:34:18,564
Maybe it'll split.

350
00:34:21,128 --> 00:34:22,573
All right!

351
00:34:24,006 --> 00:34:26,531
Okay, now we got a fair fight.

352
00:34:49,573 --> 00:34:52,560
<i>Keep your mouth shut.
I'll do the talking.</i>

353
00:34:52,618 --> 00:34:54,691
<i>You can't go in there.</i>

354
00:34:55,788 --> 00:34:58,657
<i>I told you never to walk
in here without knocking.</i>

355
00:34:58,707 --> 00:35:00,070
What's this?

356
00:35:00,125 --> 00:35:01,356
I'm not sure.

357
00:35:01,460 --> 00:35:02,823
What's it about?

358
00:35:02,836 --> 00:35:04,495
I don't know.

359
00:35:10,844 --> 00:35:12,207
Who's that?

360
00:35:12,721 --> 00:35:15,875
I think the guy in the hat
did something terrible.

361
00:35:18,477 --> 00:35:21,168
<i>- Who wants to be next?
- Like what?</i>

362
00:35:21,772 --> 00:35:23,881
You're so analytical.

363
00:35:24,608 --> 00:35:27,014
Sometimes you just
have to let art...

364
00:35:27,277 --> 00:35:28,853
flow over you.

365
00:35:31,407 --> 00:35:34,358
I'm hungry. I had this
really dirty dream.

366
00:35:34,451 --> 00:35:36,276
Was it about Karen?

367
00:35:36,328 --> 00:35:39,695
- Why do you say that?
- Why should anything have changed?

368
00:35:40,290 --> 00:35:42,115
You're the one she always wanted.

369
00:35:43,585 --> 00:35:46,359
In the old days, I wasn't emotionally
equipped to satisfy her.

370
00:35:46,422 --> 00:35:48,947
Now the equipment
doesn't work at all.

371
00:35:50,592 --> 00:35:53,081
Why do we have to talk about that?

372
00:35:54,513 --> 00:35:56,622
Come on in the kitchen with me.

373
00:36:02,354 --> 00:36:05,389
I think she found what she
was looking for in Richard.

374
00:36:06,734 --> 00:36:09,341
Be careful what you
want, young lady...

375
00:36:09,778 --> 00:36:12,101
or you will surely get it.

376
00:36:19,038 --> 00:36:21,029
What're you doing up?
Why didn't you come in?

377
00:36:21,081 --> 00:36:22,721
I didn't realize
anybody else was up.

378
00:36:24,877 --> 00:36:27,069
I've been thinking about
your friend Alex.

379
00:36:27,171 --> 00:36:29,162
Did you ever meet him?

380
00:36:29,339 --> 00:36:32,908
Karen's told me some.
I'm imagining mostly.

381
00:36:33,469 --> 00:36:36,670
I never sleep through the night.
Insomnia. Karen doesn't know.

382
00:36:36,722 --> 00:36:39,792
I might have something
that can help.

383
00:36:40,934 --> 00:36:42,332
No, thanks.

384
00:36:42,811 --> 00:36:44,256
I don't mind it.

385
00:36:44,313 --> 00:36:49,590
Sometimes when my family's asleep,
I sit downstairs and it's so quiet.

386
00:36:49,693 --> 00:36:53,476
I hate not being able to sleep,
but I don't mind the time alone.

387
00:36:54,239 --> 00:36:59,351
Sometimes I think the thing about
kids is their instant priorities.

388
00:36:59,411 --> 00:37:02,529
You know you must protect
and provide for them...

389
00:37:02,623 --> 00:37:07,117
and sometimes it means your life
isn't exactly how you want it to be.

390
00:37:09,088 --> 00:37:10,830
There's some...

391
00:37:10,881 --> 00:37:13,999
asshole at work you
have to kowtow to...

392
00:37:14,093 --> 00:37:18,586
and sometimes you do things
you never thought you'd do.

393
00:37:18,806 --> 00:37:21,627
But you try to
minimize that stuff...

394
00:37:21,683 --> 00:37:24,209
and be the best person you can be.

395
00:37:26,105 --> 00:37:30,468
But you set your priorities.
And that's the way life is.

396
00:37:30,859 --> 00:37:33,385
I wonder if your
friend Alex knew that.

397
00:37:34,321 --> 00:37:37,557
One thing's for sure:
he couldn't live with it.

398
00:37:40,577 --> 00:37:44,028
I know I shouldn't talk.
You guys knew him.

399
00:37:44,623 --> 00:37:46,483
But the thing is...

400
00:37:47,042 --> 00:37:50,077
nobody said it was going to be fun.

401
00:37:51,547 --> 00:37:53,823
At least nobody said it to me.

402
00:38:08,147 --> 00:38:11,550
You can't run in those shoes.
I'll get you some good shoes.

403
00:38:14,862 --> 00:38:18,846
I'm about to tell you something
I'm not supposed to tell anyone.

404
00:38:20,200 --> 00:38:22,192
Then maybe you shouldn't.

405
00:38:22,369 --> 00:38:24,361
I already told Alex.

406
00:38:24,455 --> 00:38:26,564
Look what happened to him.

407
00:38:33,088 --> 00:38:36,325
In a few months, a very
large corporation...

408
00:38:36,383 --> 00:38:40,533
a conglomerate, is going to
buy my very small company.

409
00:38:40,637 --> 00:38:44,705
Anyone who has our stock
will triple their money.

410
00:38:46,977 --> 00:38:50,131
That's how Alex could
afford to buy the land.

411
00:38:51,982 --> 00:38:55,100
I was thinking you could
use the information...

412
00:38:55,152 --> 00:38:57,428
to get into another line of work.

413
00:38:58,530 --> 00:39:01,019
You never learn, do you?

414
00:39:02,284 --> 00:39:05,485
By telling you, I've violated
about 16 regulations...

415
00:39:05,496 --> 00:39:07,819
of the Securities
Exchange Commission.

416
00:39:07,873 --> 00:39:09,982
So please don't repeat it.

417
00:39:10,042 --> 00:39:11,617
Repeat what?

418
00:39:19,218 --> 00:39:21,042
I loved Alex.

419
00:39:23,722 --> 00:39:26,211
What happened between
him and Sarah...

420
00:39:26,266 --> 00:39:28,506
hurt, I can't deny that.

421
00:39:29,019 --> 00:39:31,212
But that was five years ago.

422
00:39:32,022 --> 00:39:33,551
We all got over it.

423
00:39:36,193 --> 00:39:38,718
I think they felt as bad as I did.

424
00:39:42,366 --> 00:39:43,941
You know...

425
00:39:45,703 --> 00:39:48,738
they only slept
together a few times.

426
00:39:51,125 --> 00:39:55,192
But in a way, their affair had
been going on since Ann Arbor.

427
00:39:56,547 --> 00:39:58,786
She didn't marry Alex.

428
00:40:05,973 --> 00:40:07,501
You'll explain everything?

429
00:40:07,599 --> 00:40:09,175
I'll explain to them.

430
00:40:09,393 --> 00:40:11,253
Have a safe trip.

431
00:40:29,288 --> 00:40:33,355
That's the trouble with these. You
must watch them every minute.

432
00:40:39,923 --> 00:40:41,915
Did I miss Karen and Richard?

433
00:40:41,967 --> 00:40:43,365
Nope.

434
00:40:43,469 --> 00:40:46,290
Just Richard. Karen's
staying the weekend.

435
00:40:46,388 --> 00:40:47,619
But not Richard?

436
00:40:47,681 --> 00:40:50,040
Went back to be with the kids.

437
00:40:51,310 --> 00:40:53,170
That's interesting.

438
00:40:53,896 --> 00:40:56,088
How did Richard feel about it?

439
00:40:56,607 --> 00:41:00,674
If you sleep this late, you'll
miss a few mini-dramas.

440
00:41:00,778 --> 00:41:04,014
I just hope you'll wake
me for anything ugly.

441
00:41:06,867 --> 00:41:10,518
How do actors learn all those lines?
How do you remember them?

442
00:41:10,579 --> 00:41:13,946
My wife used to run them with
me, but now my maid does.

443
00:41:14,041 --> 00:41:16,648
- Your maid?
- That's how she learned English.

444
00:41:16,710 --> 00:41:20,326
Sarah says to make three
of those milks nonfat.

445
00:41:20,422 --> 00:41:21,998
Sure you don't mind this?

446
00:41:22,049 --> 00:41:24,918
I'll never remember that. Will you?

447
00:41:25,094 --> 00:41:26,574
I don't know.

448
00:41:27,429 --> 00:41:30,120
If we'd gotten married,
we'd go shopping like this.

449
00:41:30,307 --> 00:41:34,090
No, if we'd gotten married,
I'd be doing this alone.

450
00:41:36,897 --> 00:41:40,964
No, I did not say that, Molly.
I said we'll see.

451
00:41:42,736 --> 00:41:45,558
I don't have to explain
it, young lady.

452
00:41:47,032 --> 00:41:51,182
I want you to do it because
I said so. Understand?

453
00:41:55,124 --> 00:41:57,862
When you're a mother
you can be mean.

454
00:42:00,671 --> 00:42:04,406
All right, you can do that.
Tell Carmelina I said it's okay.

455
00:42:04,591 --> 00:42:07,876
I love you, sweetheart.
Daddy will call you later.

456
00:42:09,138 --> 00:42:12,255
Sometimes I don't believe
what I hear myself saying.

457
00:42:26,739 --> 00:42:30,058
<i>So you came back from Vietnam...</i>

458
00:42:30,159 --> 00:42:32,684
<i>a changed man.</i>

459
00:42:33,120 --> 00:42:36,237
<i>Well, why don't you
just tell everybody?</i>

460
00:42:36,415 --> 00:42:38,489
<i>Then, in 1972...</i>

461
00:42:38,542 --> 00:42:40,900
<i>you returned to the
University of Michigan...</i>

462
00:42:40,919 --> 00:42:43,195
<i>to enter the doctoral
program in psychology.</i>

463
00:42:43,255 --> 00:42:47,287
<i>But you couldn't seem to
finish that dissertation.</i>

464
00:42:47,384 --> 00:42:52,045
<i>I could have. I chose not to.</i>

465
00:42:52,097 --> 00:42:55,382
<i>I'm not hung up on
this completion thing.</i>

466
00:42:55,434 --> 00:42:58,386
<i>Then you had many jobs,
all of which you quit.</i>

467
00:42:58,437 --> 00:43:02,220
<i>What are you getting at?
I was evolving.</i>

468
00:43:02,274 --> 00:43:04,597
I'm still evolving.

469
00:43:05,736 --> 00:43:09,020
But your real fame came as
a radio psychologist...

470
00:43:09,073 --> 00:43:11,479
on KSFO in San Francisco.

471
00:43:12,076 --> 00:43:15,858
I wouldn't call it fame exactly.
I had a small...

472
00:43:15,996 --> 00:43:18,319
deeply disturbed following.

473
00:43:19,375 --> 00:43:21,033
What are you doing...

474
00:43:21,877 --> 00:43:23,026
now?

475
00:43:23,087 --> 00:43:27,367
Or I should say, what have
you evolved into now?

476
00:43:29,968 --> 00:43:32,126
Oh, I'm in sales.

477
00:43:32,304 --> 00:43:34,331
What are you selling?

478
00:43:36,058 --> 00:43:38,049
I don't have to answer that.

479
00:43:39,311 --> 00:43:40,922
We're leaving. Have you seen Chloe?

480
00:43:40,979 --> 00:43:43,172
We're on the air here.

481
00:43:44,650 --> 00:43:45,881
Sorry.

482
00:43:47,486 --> 00:43:49,180
Sorry, pal. Got to go.

483
00:43:49,238 --> 00:43:50,980
Just answer that last question.

484
00:43:50,989 --> 00:43:53,396
I said, "I've got to go."

485
00:44:06,714 --> 00:44:08,214
So what happened to your partner?

486
00:44:08,215 --> 00:44:10,704
He wasn't my partner.
He had the idea for the club.

487
00:44:10,801 --> 00:44:13,788
He's out of it now.
We weren't conducive.

488
00:44:13,846 --> 00:44:17,379
We got together and hypered
each other into a frenzy.

489
00:44:17,808 --> 00:44:20,499
His wife left for a younger
woman, he couldn't make love.

490
00:44:20,561 --> 00:44:23,845
He was hospitalized for
being such a nerd.

491
00:44:25,399 --> 00:44:27,141
So he's out of it?

492
00:44:27,192 --> 00:44:30,642
Yeah, he's out. It's just
me, looking for investors.

493
00:44:30,696 --> 00:44:35,724
Alex and I made love the night
before he died. It was fantastic.

494
00:44:38,537 --> 00:44:41,773
He went out with a
bang, not a whimper.

495
00:44:45,002 --> 00:44:47,278
They're either married or gay.

496
00:44:47,337 --> 00:44:50,906
If they're not gay, they've broken
up with the most wonderful woman...

497
00:44:50,966 --> 00:44:54,701
or they've broken up with
a bitch who looks like me.

498
00:44:55,137 --> 00:44:59,500
They're in transition from a monogamous
relationship and need space.

499
00:44:59,600 --> 00:45:02,836
Or they're tired of
space, but can't commit.

500
00:45:02,936 --> 00:45:05,544
Or they want to commit but
are afraid to get close.

501
00:45:05,647 --> 00:45:08,884
They want to get close and
you don't want them near.

502
00:45:08,984 --> 00:45:10,762
Can't be that bad.

503
00:45:10,861 --> 00:45:12,306
You don't know.

504
00:45:12,696 --> 00:45:15,814
I've been out there
dating for 20 years.

505
00:45:15,866 --> 00:45:19,684
I know in the first 15 seconds
if there's a chance in the world.

506
00:45:19,745 --> 00:45:21,819
At least you're giving
them a fair shot.

507
00:45:21,872 --> 00:45:25,488
Easy for you to say. Married
to Harold, the perfect man.

508
00:45:26,210 --> 00:45:29,743
Sometimes I think I don't
